If I were overspending my income at that rate--and even without knowing what
your income is that looks pretty extreme regardless--I wouldn't be eating
out AT ALL and I wouldn't be buying clothing or household goods anyplace
except thrift stores. I'd also be looking at every able-bodied adult in the
household getting a second job until the spending got back in line with the
income. I don't mean to focus on restaurant food as the source of your
problem, but "we don't eat out that much" tells me you have a mentality that
it's somehow okay to buy things you can't afford, things you might think
you're somehow entitled to anyway.

You're probably right, you can't excise an entire category (unless you've
budgeted for entertainment and vacations, in which case that should be the
first to go to zero), but I suspect you need to look first at the areas of
large expense which for most people are housing and cars. If you can't buy
the things your family needs and still make your mortgage payment, you need
to move to a cheaper house or even an apartment. If you're making one or
more car payments and can't afford them, you need to trade that car for one
you can afford. And so on. See a pattern here?
