Not to sound trite, but the person you need to find is yourself.  Your
wife AND oldest daughter started college without your having the
funding to support that?  And you have more kids?!?  Are you expecting
the tooth fairy to fly in and rescue you?

In a way, you may be to blame for for the mess, by not including DW in
tracking of finances and leaving her out of "the loop."  If so, you'd
better admit that up front.

Sample script:
"Dear wife, this is a partnership and our finances are screwed up.  I
thought paying for college was possible, but it is not.  We have to
look at our long term survival and re-evaluate what we can afford.  As
the only one bringing in money, and not enough of it, I have to say
that we have to make a choice - dear daughter goes to college on our
money and you help support us - even if it means your dropping out of
college yourself - or dear daughter has to fend for herself and you
have to still help find a way of cutting our expenses and supporting
your college while we meet our other financial goals.  Otherwise, we
can't afford your going to college either.  Here is our situation and
this is the projection of where we will be if we continue like
this..."

You are not a sack of unlimited money with a protruding penis.  Your
family (and you) needs to recognize that.

BTW, do you plan to stiff the younger daughter on college funding,
either by intent or financial mismanagement?  You'll not create any
love doing that, especially if you have even partially funded daughter
#1.  Daughter #2 won't like mom either, for putting you in those
financial straits.

The bottom line is you cannot give what you do not have.  You are
avoiding a confrontation by trying to throw money at the problem to
make it go away.  It won't.   You must have the battle, and the sooner
the better.  Unless you plan to die before age 70, you have a
retirement and emergency fund that you absolutely must fund.
Daughter(s) may abandon you, wife may divorce you, and you may end up
with nothing but memories and their debts.  It didn't used to be that
way, but unless you have a rock solid marriage, then those are
possibilities.   Frankly, if you can't discuss financial realities,
then I don't think you have a rock solid marriage.  You might be
better off having the big fight now and divorcing while you have zero
financial worth, hoping that a judge has better financial sense than
you when he awards support and alimony.

If your wife is a worthy partner, she'll be angry and upset, but
willing to do what is needed to make things work.

If they don't think having to give up college  or find a way to help
out is fair, then I suggest you quit your job and go to college
yourself.

Obviously, I don't know the entire situation, only what you have
presented.  If DD and DW are in expensive colleges, they may have to
