">

How about this?  Instead of starting with your current expenditures as a
baseline, start with your income as the baseline.  Then make a budget by
slicing it up according to your priorities, rather than what you are
spending in each category now.  This will give you the mental picture of
how you need to start living.  When you are done, *then* compare it to
what you are spending in each category now.

Then, if you haven't done it already, have a sit-down talk with your
wife and older kids.  Tell them about it a day or two in advance, make
it a real event.  Explain the problem with *specific numbers* and then
have a brainstorming session with the only criteria being, we only
consider things that will actually fix the problem.  In other words,
spending must re-align to what is available rather than the status quo
or what people deserve.  Start off the brainstorming by suggesting
something drastic, like moving to a smaller house and cutting back to 1
car.  If you're overspending by 50%, you have start right off by making
them realize the status quo is *dead*... but we can and will make it
through.

I sympathize.  Cutting back is very hard.  But if you've just burned
through your net worth in 2 years, now is the last possible moment to
hit the brakes before plunging into the abyss.  Just keep telling
yourself, the longer I wait, the larger the problem will be.
