&gt; expenses with me and help me create a budget. I'm willing to pay for the
&gt; services of a professional but how do I find one?
">

In some circumstances, it's pretty normal to spend more than you make.  For
instance, most people going to college spend more during their college years
than they make during their college years.  The day you buy a house, you've
probably spent more than you make in a year, or two, or three.

There are generally two ways to cover gaps like this.  One is save up for
them beforehand.  The other is borrow the money and pay it back in the
future.  Or both.

One thing that will probably not help much is spending even more, even if
it's for the professional services of an astute money manager.  If your
family is spending 50% more than it takes in, no professional advice is
going to magically produce more money.

As to how do you find a professional, you do it the same way you find a
doctor, dentist, auto mechanic, or whatever.  Ask your colleagues at work
and your neighbors who they use and shop around.
